          "instruction": "Answer the questions based on the audio.",
          "prompt_html": "<h1>NOTE COMPLETION 19</h1><p><strong>Questions 31 - 36</strong></p><p>Complete the notes. Use <strong>NO MORE THAN THREE WORDS AND / OR A NUMBER</strong> for each answer.</p><p><strong>The Super Volcano</strong></p><ul><li><p>No precise scientific definition - used to describe volcanoes responsible for the Earth’s largest volcanic eruptions.</p></li><li><p>Super volcano eruptions form calderas. Unlike normal volcano craters, which generally measure in the hundreds of metres, calderas often reach a sizes of up to <blank data-qid=\"q31\"/> miles wide.</p></li></ul><table><thead><tr><th>Super volcano caldera locations:</th><th>Long Valley, Eastern California</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>(not all active)</td><td>Toba, Indonesia</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Lake Taupo, <blank data-qid=\"q32\"/></td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Japan</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Indonesia</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Scotland</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Alaska</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Normal volcano formation - Magma column rises from Earth, erupts and becomes hard on sides creating the familiar <blank data-qid=\"q33\"/> mountain.</p><p>Super volcano formation - <blank data-qid=\"q34\"/> is created in the Earth's crust due to the rising of magma from Earth’s mantle. Chamber increases to enormous size, creating colossal pressure. Eruption finally forms massive caldera.</p><p>Results of super volcano eruption</p><ul><li><p>Ash, dust and sulphur dioxide ejected, blocking sun and creating cold wave lasting several years. Plants and animals (including humans) would die.</p></li><li><p>Most recent caldera-forming eruption (<blank data-qid=\"q35\"/> years ago approx.). Ash, pumice, and gases covered more than 3,000 square miles and also went high into the stratosphere to circle the Earth, affecting its <blank data-qid=\"q36\"/>. Ash from this eruption still found in Iowa and in drill cores from the Gulf of Mexico.</p></li></ul>",
